04299nam a22006375i 9780520390409DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203904097 a10.1525/97805203904092doi  a(DE-B1597)627299  a(OCoLC)1356995514  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aTX353b.H334 2023eb 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a338.4/7664223/eng/202208031 aHaushofer, Lisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWonder Foods :bThe Science and Commerce of Nutrition /cLisa Haushofer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v8000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Balloons over Indianapolis -- t1 • “Focussed Flesh” -- t2 • The Raw and the Civilized -- t3 • Digestive Economies -- t4 • A Physiology of Consumption -- t5 • The Brewer, the Baker, and the Health Food Maker -- tConclusion: Transparent Man on Man-Made Land -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1850 and 1950, experts and entrepreneurs in Britain and the United States forged new connections between the nutrition sciences and the commercial realm through their enthusiasm for new edible consumables. The resulting food products promised wondrous solutions for what seemed both individual and social ills. By examining products like Gail Borden's meat biscuit, Benger's Food, Kellogg's health foods, Fleischmann's yeast, and food yeast, Wonder Foods shows how new products dazzled with visions of modernity, efficiency, and scientific progress even as they perpetuated exclusionary views about who deserved to eat, thrive, and live. Drawing on extensive archival research, historian Lisa Haushofer reveals that the story of modern food and nutrition was not about innocuous technological advances or superior scientific insights but rather the powerful logic of exploitation and economization that undergirded colonial and industrial food projects. In the process, these wonder food products have shaped both modern food regimes and how we think about food.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFood industry and tradexEconomic aspects. 0aFoodxTechnological innovationsxHistory. 0aNutritionxEconomic aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW0 cprintz978052039038640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520390409?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520390409423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520390409/original  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099451-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishb2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2022  aZDB-23-PLWb2022  aZDB-23-UCY